# Trivy suppressions — documented, justified, and expiring.
#
# The image scan fails the build on CRITICAL/HIGH with `ignore-unfixed: true`,
# so only vulnerabilities that HAVE a fix available can break CI. That is the
# right default: if upstream shipped a patch, we should take it.
#
# Reality check: base-image CVEs are a treadmill. Debian publishes new advisories
# constantly, and the weekly scheduled scan can go red without a single line of
# SENTRIX changing. When that happens, the correct order of preference is:
#
#   1. Rebuild — `apt-get upgrade` in the runtime stage often already fixes it.
#   2. Bump the base image tag.
#   3. Only then, suppress HERE — with a CVE id, a reason, and an expiry date.
#
# Never suppress something reachable from application code. These are for
# base-image noise that we cannot patch and that our attack surface doesn't
# touch (e.g. a CVE in a Debian utility the container never executes).
#
# Format:  CVE-YYYY-NNNNN   # reason — reviewed YYYY-MM-DD, expires YYYY-MM-DD
#
# (empty — the runtime stage patches the OS and upgrades pip/setuptools/wheel,
#  which removed the setuptools CVE-2024-6345 / CVE-2025-47273 findings that
#  originally failed this gate. Add entries only with justification.)
